John:

I did not mean to imply that Wells had all the answers, merely that he 
appears to be an acknowledged expert in the field, which I am not, and I 
was passing on what he told me regarding the substitution of &quot;chr&quot; for &quot;tr.&quot;

I have not looked at the lexical sets you have been writing about, but 
since Wells invented them, I assume there is no set which includes that 
substitution.  Do you have any reason to suspect that a significant 
proportion of any speech population anywhere makes this substitution?   
Can you point me to a dictionary that lists the substitution as an 
accepted pronunciation for &quot;train&quot;?

The point I was getting at is that although there is a tremendous 
variation in spoken English from one dialect to another, there is a 
distinction which I feel needs to be made between spelling according to 
one&#39;s dialect and spelling according to a speech pathology (if that is 
the appropriate term), such as a lisp.  Do people who speak with a lisp 
hear their lisp or not?  I would think if they don&#39;t hear it, they would 
have no reason to write it into a QS word since they would think they 
spoke like everyone else in their area and the rest of the people aren&#39;t 
lisping.  If they do hear it in their own speech, then they should 
realize that isn&#39;t the way everyone else speaks in their area, so they 
should be able to avoid including an oddity of their own idiolect in 
their QS.

Paige

